    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided financial statement notes, the **common-control recast accounting treatment** is applied when entities that share the same controlling financial interest (in this case, Mr. Elon Musk, who held majority voting interests in SpaceX, xAI, and X) are merged. Instead of treating the merger as a standard market acquisition, it is accounted for as a **reorganization of entities under common control**. \n\nHere is how this accounting treatment affects the historical financial statements:\n\n### 1. Retrospective Combination at Historical Carrying Amounts\n* **Net Assets:** The consolidated financial statements are retrospectively recast to combine the net assets of SpaceX, xAI, and X for **all periods presented**, using their **historical carrying amounts** (book values) rather than fair market values.\n* **No Goodwill:** Because this is a reorganization under common control rather than an external acquisition, **no new goodwill or other intangible assets are recorded**.\n\n### 2. Elimination of Intercompany Transactions\n* All historical related-party transactions and intercompany balances between SpaceX, xAI, and X are **eliminated in consolidation** across all historical periods presented, as if they had always been a single entity.\n\n### 3. Equity and Capital Stock Adjustments\n* **Exchange Ratios:** The capital stock and shareholders’ equity for all historical periods reflect a continuation of SpaceX’s historical equity, combined with the historical equity of X and xAI. These are retroactively adjusted using the **exchange ratios** established to effect the mergers (e.g., converting X Common Stock to xAI Common Stock, and ultimately to SpaceX Common Stock).\n* **Change in Reporting Entity:** This retrospective presentation constitutes a formal **change in reporting entity**. Consequently, **separate historical financial statements for xAI and X are not provided**, as the consolidated statements already reflect the combined entity for all periods.\n\n### 4. Exception for xAI’s Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock\n* **No Retrospective Recast:** Unlike the common stock, xAI’s historical Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock is **not retrospectively recast** on an as-converted basis for periods prior to the merger. \n* **Preservation of Legal Form:** Because the preferred stock represented a separate equity class of a legally distinct predecessor entity, the historical balance sheets continue to reflect it as outstanding preferred stock consistent with its legal form and rights at the time. The conversion into SpaceX Common Stock is only recognized prospectively in the period the merger actually closed (Q1 2026).\n\n### 5. Retroactive Adjustment for Stock Splits\n* **2026 Stock Split:** The company effected a five-for-one forward stock split on May 4, 2026. Under this recast treatment, **all historical share and per-share information** (as well as preferred stock conversion rates) is **retroactively adjusted** to reflect the stock split for all periods presented. \n\nIn summary, the common-control recast treatment essentially rewrites the financial history of the company as if SpaceX, xAI, and X had always been a single consolidated entity, strictly utilizing historical book values, eliminating internal transactions, and retroactively applying stock splits and common-stock exchange ratios.',
