        output='Based on the provided S-1 prospectus excerpts, here are the subscriber, usage, and key operating metrics disclosed by the company, along with the strategic context for each:\n\n### 1. Subscriber Metrics\n**Starlink Subscribers**\n*   **Definition:** Defined as a unique "Service Line" (an individual instance of service provisioned under a subscription plan). It includes Personal (Residential, Roam) and Business plans but *excludes* managed enterprise and government customers with direct negotiated contracts. \n*   **Q1 2026:** ~10.3 million (up 105% YoY).\n*   **Q1 2025:** ~5.0 million (up 91% YoY).\n*   **Historical (Year-End):** 8.9M (2025), 4.4M (2024), 2.3M (2023).\n*   **Market Reach:** Across 164 countries/territories, representing a small fraction of the ~3.3 billion potential end-users in served markets.\n\n**Starlink Subscriber ARPU (Average Revenue Per User)**\n*   **Definition:** Service revenue divided by the average number of subscribers and the number of months in the period.\n*   **Q1 2026:** $66 / month.\n*   **Q1 2025:** $86 / month.\n*   **Historical (Year-End):** $81 (2025), $91 (2024), $99 (2023).\n*   **Strategy:** The company prioritizes scale, operational efficiencies, and global market access over ARPU growth. ARPU is expected to continue declining due to international expansion and the introduction of lower-priced service plans.\n\n**X and Grok Paid Subscribers**\n*   **Q1 2026:** ~6.3 million active paid subscribers.\n*   **Breakdown:** ~4.4 million X Premium/Premium+ subscribers and ~1.9 million SuperGrok/SuperGrok Heavy/SuperGrok Lite subscribers.\n\n**Satellite-to-Mobile Devices**\n*   **Q1 2026:** ~7.4 million monthly unique devices utilizing satellite-to-mobile texting and over-the-top voice services across ~30 countries.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Usage Metrics\n**Monthly Active Users (MAU) for X and Grok**\n*   **Definition:** Unique registered users who interacted with Grok or X via web or mobile at least once in a 30-day period. The company deduplicates users who access both platforms based on sign-in traffic.\n*   **Q1 2026:** ~550 million MAUs (with >1.3 billion supported accounts active in the trailing 12 months).\n*   **Q4 2025:** ~520 million MAUs (with >1.1 billion supported accounts).\n*   **Grok AI Usage:** ~117 million MAUs specifically utilized Grok’s AI features as of March 31, 2026.\n*   **Strategy:** While MAU measures scale and engagement, management explicitly states they are focused on revenue and operating margins, *not* on prioritizing the growth or maintenance of MAU levels.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Key Operating Metrics\n**Space Segment (Launch & Orbit Capacity)**\n*   **Mass to Orbit:** 556 metric tons (Q1 2026) vs. 450 metric tons (Q1 2025). Full-year 2025 totaled 2,213 metric tons.\n*   **Launches:** 40 launches (Q1 2026) vs. 38 launches (Q1 2025). Full-year 2025 totaled 170 launches. *(Note: Starship launches are currently classified as internal, not customer launches).*\n*   **Satellite Constellation Scale:** ~9,600 Starlink broadband and mobile satellites in Low-Earth Orbit (LEO) as of March 31, 2026, accounting for ~75% of all active maneuverable satellites in orbit. \n\n**AI Segment (Compute Infrastructure)**\n*   **Nameplate Compute Draw:** 1 Gigawatt (GW) (Q1 2026) vs. 0.3 GW (Q1 2025). Full-year 2025 was 0.8 GW. This reflects the massive scale of their AI data center expansions and GPU hardware deployments.\n\n**Network Performance (Starlink Broadband)**\n*   **Latency:** Median of ~25 milliseconds (with round-trip latencies as low as 21 ms).\n*   **Download Speeds:** Median of 225 Mbps during peak hours for residential users (with capabilities exceeding 400 Mbps). \n*   **Future Capacity:** The company plans to deploy next-generation "V3" satellites via Starship in H2 2026, offering 1 Tbps of downlink capacity per satellite (a 20-fold increase per launch compared to Falcon 9).',
