    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided financial statement excerpts, here is a detailed breakdown of the company\'s intercompany eliminations, related party transactions, and revenue recognition policies across its segments.\n\n### 1. Intercompany Eliminations\n*   **Consolidation Principle:** All intercompany balances and transactions are eliminated in the preparation of the consolidated financial statements.\n*   **Common Control Mergers:** Following the 2025/2026 mergers of xAI and X into SpaceX (accounted for as reorganizations of entities under common control), all historical related party transactions between these entities were eliminated in consolidation for all periods presented.\n*   **Inter-Segment Starlink Launches:** The Space segment does **not** recognize any inter-segment revenue for launches dedicated to deploying the company\'s own Starlink satellites. Instead, the associated launch costs are capitalized within the Connectivity segment (in *Property, plant, and equipment, net*) and depreciated over time. Space segment revenue strictly reflects external customer launches and activities.\n\n### 2. Related Party Transactions\n*   **Audit Committee Policy:** The company has a written policy requiring the audit committee to review and approve/disapprove "related person transactions." A related person transaction is defined as any transaction involving the company where the amount exceeds **$120,000** and a related person has a direct or indirect material interest. \n*   **Definition of Related Persons:** Includes executive officers, directors, beneficial owners of >5% of voting securities, and their immediate family members or household sharers.\n*   **Elon Musk & Affiliated Entities:** Disclosures explicitly track transactions involving CEO Elon Musk, noting his external affiliations (e.g., serving as CEO and ~20% shareholder of Tesla, and founder of other ventures).\n*   **xAI Merger Inclusion:** Ongoing agreements and transactions originally entered into by xAI or X Holdings prior to the merger are included in the related party transaction disclosures.\n*   **Financial Statement References:** The consolidated balance sheet includes a footnote referencing **Note 18, Related Party Transactions**, and the independent auditor\'s report identifies "Significant Transactions with Related Parties" as a key area of the audit.\n\n### 3. Revenue Recognition Policies\nThe company recognizes revenue when control of goods or services is transferred to the customer, either **"over time"** or at a **"point in time,"** depending on the segment and contract specifics.\n\n#### A. Space Segment\nRevenue is derived from fixed-price contracts for Launch Services (1–5 years) and Launch & Development (1–14 years).\n*   **Launch Services (Point in Time):** Revenue and costs are deferred and recognized at a **point in time** upon the launch or deployment of the customer’s payload to its intended orbit. This is due to the interchangeability of flight hardware and minimal unique engineering costs.\n*   **Launch and Development (Over Time):** Revenue is recognized **over time** because the work creates an asset with no alternative use, and the company has an enforceable right to payment for performance to date.\n*   **Cost-to-Cost Input Method:** For over-time contracts, progress is measured using the **cost-to-cost method** (costs incurred to date relative to total estimated costs at completion). This requires significant management judgment regarding launch timing, labor hours, shared costs for reusable rockets, and technological changes. Estimate changes are recognized on a cumulative basis.\n\n#### B. Connectivity Segment\nRevenue is generated from Starlink broadband, Starlink Mobile, Starshield, and hardware sales.\n*   **Broadband & Mobile Services (Over Time):** Recognized **over time** as the customer simultaneously receives and consumes the benefits. Revenue is recognized ratably over the subscription term or based on actual data usage. Advanced payments are recorded as deferred revenue. Contracts are generally month-to-month.\n*   **Starlink Kits / Hardware (Point in Time):** Recognized at a **point in time** when control transfers (typically upon delivery or installation for enterprise customers). Revenue is reported net of returns and chargebacks. Shipping and handling are treated as fulfillment activities, not separate performance obligations.\n*   **Starshield Contracts (Over Time):** Long-term, multi-year government/national security contracts are recognized **over time** using the **cost-to-cost input method**, similar to the Space segment\'s development contracts.\n*   **Multiple Performance Obligations:** Contracts containing both services and hardware are bifurcated. The transaction price is allocated based on the standalone selling price of each distinct obligation.\n\n#### C. AI Segment (X / xAI)\nRevenue is generated from digital platform services, including advertising, subscriptions, and data licensing.\n*   **Advertising Services (Point in Time):** Recognized when the ad is delivered and user engagement criteria are met. \n    *   *Gross Basis:* When the company acts as the principal (direct sales).\n    *   *Net Basis:* When the company acts as an agent (sales through Supply Side Platform partners who control inventory and pricing).\n*   **Premium Subscriptions (Over Time):** Revenue for X and Grok subscriptions is recognized **ratably** over the subscription term (ranging from month-to-month to one year).\n*   **Data Licensing:** Grants access to historical or real-time IP. \n    *   *Historical IP:* Recognized at a **point in time**.\n    *   *Future IP:* Recognized on a **straight-line basis** over the period the data is provided. If multiple obligations exist, revenue is allocated based on standalone selling prices.\n\n#### D. Critical Audit Matter (CAM)\nThe independent auditor identified **"Revenue Recognition – Estimate of Total Cost at Completion for Certain Contracts Recognized Over Time"** as a Critical Audit Matter. This is due to the high degree of subjective management judgment and complex assumptions required to estimate total costs for the cost-to-cost input method used in both the Space (reusable vehicles, launch timing) and Connectivity (satellite production, shared costs) segments.',
