    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided financial statement notes and disclosures, here are the details regarding the company\'s share-based compensation, stock class structure, and valuation methodologies:\n\n### 1. Share-Based Compensation Details\n**Award Types & Expense Recognition Policies**\n*   **Types of Awards:** The company grants stock options, Restricted Share Units (RSUs), Restricted Share Awards (RSAs), Stock Appreciation Rights (SARs), and offers an Employee Share Purchase Plan (ESPP).\n*   **Expense Recognition:** \n    *   *Service Conditions:* Recognized on a straight-line basis over the requisite service period.\n    *   *Performance Conditions:* Recognized on a graded vesting basis only when the vesting condition becomes probable.\n    *   *Forfeitures:* Accounted for as they occur (not estimated upfront).\n*   **Capitalization & Taxes:** Share-based compensation capitalized to the balance sheets was $154 million, $132 million, and $108 million for the years ended December 31, 2025, 2024, and 2023, respectively. No income tax benefits were recognized due to a valuation allowance on U.S. deferred tax assets.\n\n**Financial Impact (Expense Breakdown)**\nTotal share-based compensation expense for 2025, 2024, and 2023 was **$1,947 million**, **$784 million**, and **$679 million**, respectively. \n*   *Cost of Revenue:* $253M (2025) | $193M (2024) | $167M (2023)\n*   *Research & Development:* $859M (2025) | $230M (2024) | $179M (2023)\n*   *Selling, General & Administrative:* $835M (2025) | $360M (2024) | $333M (2023)\n*   *Unvested Expense:* As of December 31, 2025, $4,842 million of total remaining expense is expected to be recognized over a weighted-average period of 3.2 years.\n\n**Notable Executive & Employee Awards**\n*   **Elon Musk’s "xAI Award" (Nov 2025) & "AI CEO Award" (March 2026):** The xAI Award (12 tranches tied to $213B–$1,313B valuation milestones and a $2B capital raise) was cancelled in March 2026 and replaced by the **AI CEO Award**. The new award consists of 302.1 million performance-based Class B restricted shares tied to market cap milestones ($1.065T to $6.565T) and the completion of non-Earth-based data centers delivering 100 terawatts of compute/year. Treated as an accounting modification, no expense was recognized as of March 31, 2026, because the milestones were deemed improbable.\n*   **SpaceX CEO Award:** Similar to the AI CEO Award, performance milestones are currently considered improbable, and no expense has been recognized.\n*   **CFO Award (Bret Johnsen):** Amended in January 2026. 4 million performance-based stock options now vest based on adjusted EBITDA milestones ($10 billion increments from 2025–2029), followed by an additional one-year and one-day service requirement.\n*   **X Employee RSUs:** Granted in March 2023 with liquidity-event performance conditions. In 2025, the performance condition was removed, triggering additional share-based compensation expense.\n*   **Gwynne Shotwell:** Received RSUs in lieu of $726,923 of her 2025 base salary.\n\n**Merger Conversions**\n*   **xAI Merger:** xAI options, RSUs, and RSAs were converted into SpaceX equity at a **0.1433** ratio (on a pre-2026 Stock Split basis).\n*   **X Merger:** Outstanding X RSUs were converted into xAI RSUs at a **2.776** ratio.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Stock Class Structure & Earnings Per Share (EPS)\n**Stock Classes & Rights**\n*   The company has **Class A, Class B, and Class C** common stock. All classes possess identical economic rights, resulting in the same net income (loss) per share. Consequently, the company presents a single EPS figure for all common classes. \n*   *Note:* Class C common stock awards are subject to a one-for-one reclassification into Class A common stock.\n\n**EPS Methodology**\n*   **Basic EPS:** Computed using the **two-class method** required for participating securities. Certain redeemable convertible preferred stocks are considered participating securities because they are entitled to dividends on an as-converted basis, though they do not participate in net losses.\n*   **Diluted EPS:** Computed using the more dilutive of the two-class method or the if-converted method. Potentially dilutive shares (options, RSUs) are included using the treasury stock method.\n*   **Anti-Dilutive Exclusions:** For Q1 2026 and Q1 2025, the company excluded xAI Preferred Stock, SpaceX Preferred Stock, and hundreds of millions of share-based compensation awards (including 1,319.1 million awards in Q1 2026 subject to unmet performance/market conditions) from the diluted EPS calculation.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Valuation Disclosures & Methodologies\n**Valuation Models Used**\n*   **RSUs, RSAs, and ESPP:** Valued based on the fair market value of the company’s common stock on the grant date (determined via third-party 409A valuations).\n*   **Standard Stock Options:** Valued using the **Black-Scholes option-pricing model**.\n*   **CEO Awards (Market/Performance Conditions):** Valued using a **Monte Carlo simulation model**.\n\n**Key Assumptions: Employee Stock Options (Black-Scholes)**\n*   **Expected Term:** Calculated using the simplified method (midpoint between vesting period and contractual life). *2025: 6.94 yrs | 2024: 6.80 yrs | 2023: 6.70 yrs.*\n*   **Volatility:** Based on daily historical prices of comparable public companies. *2025: 43.14% | 2024: 39.80% | 2023: 43.20%.*\n*   **Risk-Free Interest Rate:** Based on U.S. Government securities matching the expected term. *2025: 4.02% | 2024: 4.30% | 2023: 3.60%.*\n*   **Dividend Yield:** **0.00%** (The company has never paid dividends and does not anticipate doing so).\n\n**Key Assumptions: CEO Awards (Monte Carlo)**\n*   **xAI Award:** Expected term of 10.0 years; Volatility of 45%–55%; Risk-free rate of 4.06%; Dividend yield of 0.00%.\n*   **SpaceX & AI CEO Awards:** Because these awards lack a defined performance period other than continued employment, an expected term of **30 years** (the midpoint of a 10-to-50-year analysis) was used. Volatility and risk-free rates were adjusted to match this 30-year expected term using comparable public companies and U.S. Government securities. The grant date fair value of the AI CEO Award was determined to be **$91.47 to $95.92 per share**.',
